Siso's representations of earth and water in a new exhibition
"People Swimming in the Swimming Pool" from the year 2022 is a work of art by Vicente Siso, which will be exhibited from January 13th in the "Tierra del Sol" gallery (photo provided by Vicente Siso)
"Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" - this is the title of the exhibition in the new location of the "Tierra del Sol" gallery in West Hollywood. Siso has been part of the Studio Arts Program as an artist since 2012 and is now showing his first solo exhibition. Siso was born in Madrid in 1962 and grew up in Venezuela, Trinidad and Miami. At the age of eight, he moved with his family to Southern California.
In numerous series of landscapes, portraits and still lifes with acrylic, pastel, charcoal or watercolor, Siso shows his masterful skill. Inspired by family portraits, his own reference photographs and memories, his colorful compositions show the entire palette of his interests and his knowledge in different media. His tropical and maritime landscapes reflect the places of his past in detailed patterns. People are also integrated to create important connections between culture, memory and nature. Siso titles his artworks with a mixture of Spanish and English - a testament to the celebrated and important complexities of his life in Los Angeles County. The exhibition "Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" opens on Saturday, January 13, with a reception from 6:00 PM to 8:00 PM. The exhibition runs until Sunday, March 3.
Gallery "Tierra del Sol", 7414 Santa Monica Blvd. Further information can be found at tierradelsolgallery.org.
Adapt the old and integrate the new to solve problems
At the district level, we only need to take a look at Sydney's Central Business District: an originally non-urbanized landscape first transformed into a settlement with two-story buildings with a maximum height of 46 meters, and later into a city with today's dizzying towers. On a much smaller scale, this could also happen in Sydney's centers around the central traffic points. The city center districts must also continue to develop, tending towards more affordable living spaces with buildings that are further overgrown with plants in the main areas. Naturally, these newly created living spaces must be convincing in terms of design, and the plants, landscape design, and parks must be integrated into the existing essential infrastructure.
Our planning system must also adapt, so that the people responsible in the district councils of the city centers, who tend to be critical of changes, do not alone determine the future design of their neighborhoods. One possibility would be to install an independent decision-making body that is committed to high-quality concepts that extend to the height of the plants and include space for families, large balconies and community gardens - and are also visually convincing. This could be a task for the current government architect of NSW. As a basis for doing this, a carefully elaborated regulation would be needed.
Over the past 10 years, our lives have been transformed by technology. Many people work from home, and Sydney has gained an impressive network of subways and urban railways. Online shopping has changed the way we do errands, and thanks to smartphones, friends and family can stay in better contact. Precisely such adaptations from one system to another are also possible in our construction environment. In this context, the emphasis of planning should be on adaptive reuse and not on the preservation of the old.
Chris Johnson was the NSW Government Architect from 1995 to 2005 and Executive Director of the NSW Planning Department from 2005 to 2009. From 2011 to 2019 he was CEO of Urban Taskforce Australia.
A final interpellation for equality between women and men
Last year, the World Economic Forum predicted that it would take five generations to achieve gender equality in every country. Now the World Bank wants to significantly shorten this timeframe.
The international financial institution plans to introduce a strategy to significantly promote the economic opportunities of girls and women by the year 2030. The plan focuses on the goal of improving inclusion and resilience by providing access to finance, technical innovation, and changes in public policies and laws.
Recent research has shown that both social norms and ways of thinking can change, and that the integration of men and boys, for example, can help promote gender equality," reads a draft consultation of the plan. "Positive results in connection with equality can be accelerated and scaled if one better understands... how social norms and attitudes influence expectations, priorities, and daily practices."
Changes in thinking are - compared to bank loans for women in the country or school registrations for girls - more difficult to quantify. Nevertheless, there are numerous indications that show that the integration of women can move mountains. In Iran, for example, women have become the biggest threat to the Islamic government in 40 years: they have refused to observe the laws that force them to cover their hair. In some of the 130 countries with minimum quotas for women's representation in government, for example in India, male resistance to women's right to vote and political activity has diminished.
In some rural communities in Africa, civil society organizations are replacing an extremely harmful initiation rite with health education. One of these programs helped Kamanda Timayio, traditional chief of the Masai village of Maparasha, Kenya, to change his attitude towards female genital mutilation. He told Le Monde that he had "overcome his ignorance" and wanted to renounce the practice.
The World Bank cites further examples. From 1970 to 2022, the literacy rate of women in Bangladesh quadrupled and women's participation in the labor market doubled. The country's gross domestic product has tripled. The change has developed its own dynamic. The employment of women as paid teachers and health workers in the villages themselves has created trust "and has made women's mobility and professional activity more acceptable in society."
The bank's plan focuses on the norms and institutions where the generational change may not yet have occurred. In Rwanda, it took more than two decades for the country to establish itself as a model for agrarian reforms and to promote the economic empowerment of women. "It helps no one if women are kept down," said Rwandan President Paul Kagame when he spoke in favor of agrarian reform in 2015. "We must change ways of thinking, not just laws."
The World Bank hopes to be able to disseminate this message.
The farmers and locomotive drivers of Germany are scaring German entrepreneurs.
In Germany, where workers and employers together keep many companies running, large strikes are unusual. There has hardly ever been a big wave of strikes. But currently, the "land of co-determination" has to face a week of strikes, where not only angry farmers block the roads with tractors for eight days in a row, but also railway workers go on a three-day strike. And as if that weren't enough, doctors have now also threatened to strike, and already between Christmas and New Year, some medical practices had closed their doors. This "pitchfork mob," as some call it, will put the harmonious relations in Germany to the test at the beginning of the year.
The protests were apparently triggered by the government's decision to abolish diesel subsidies for agriculture and to reduce tax breaks for agricultural vehicles. These measures exceeded the farmers' understanding. They mobilized other disgruntled workers who are suffering under the burden of inflation, economic recession, and the austerity measures imposed by the government. On January 9, freight and passenger train drivers of Deutsche Bahn began a strike to protest against working hours and wages.
To reduce tensions with farmers, the government has declared itself ready to gradually reduce diesel subsidies over the next three years. The exemption from vehicle tax for agricultural vehicles should also be maintained. The farmers rejected the concessions, deeming them insufficient. On January 4, Economy Minister Robert Habeck wanted to leave a ferry after returning from vacation with his family, but an aggressive group of protesters tried to prevent this. If the locomotive drivers also prove to be unimpressed, this could become expensive for the German economy, estimates the Institute for Economic Research IW Cologne. The railway strike could cost the economy 100 million euros per day if production has to be interrupted. The automotive, chemical, and steel industries, Germany's largest economic sectors, are particularly dependent on freight transport by rail.
The atmosphere among the workers is becoming increasingly tense. "There are calls with fantasies of revolution," Habeck warned. The far-right party Alternative for Germany is doing its best to fuel these protests. In Dresden, the Free Saxons, another far-right party, infiltrated the farmers' protests and called for "extinguishing the traffic light."
Thomas Puls of the Cologne Institute for Economic Research fears that the strikes could damage Germany's reputation as an economic hub. Local entrepreneurs are already concerned that there will be a German version of the yellow vest protests, like in France in 2018, which ended with demonstrators setting cars on fire on the Champs-Élysées and police intervening with tear gas. Jochen Kopelke, head of the police union, warned in an interview with the Tagesspiegel: "The farmers' protests are probably just the beginning of a huge wave of protests that will hit us this year." Germany was the only one of the major economic regions that shrank in 2023, and the year ended on a particularly sour note: an unexpected decline in economic confidence in December. The current year could become even more difficult.
The brewers complain that the wine producers are exempted from the regulations regarding the reduction of alcohol content.
In the EU debate on regulations to reduce waste, breweries argue that the exceptions granted to winemakers in connection with reuse targets and deposit refund systems disadvantage them. However, one of the officials of the European Wine Industry Association believes that brewers "should mind their own business."
European breweries warn that it is unfair and possibly illegal to make exceptions for wine from recycling targets and deposit refund systems, but not for beer. Meanwhile, lawmakers are in the final round of discussions about a new law that is intended to turn the tide on the growing mountains of packaging waste in the EU.
The environment ministers approved a negotiating mandate of the Council of Europe before Christmas regarding the proposal to create a regulation to regulate packaging and packaging waste, and thus cleared the way for the imminent political discussions with the European Parliament, which are already underway at a technical level.
"Our position is clear," the umbrella association of European brewers, Brewers of Europe, wrote to the members of the European Parliament and the government negotiators (January 10). "If the goals and regulations of the packaging and packaging waste regulation apply to beer, there is a legal obligation to apply them to all categories of alcoholic beverages."
At their supreme meeting on December 18, the ministers decided on an exception for winegrowers from the obligation to offer 10% of products in reusable containers in a reuse or refill system, and that until the end of the decade. By the year 2040, this share should increase to 40%. This exception should also apply to the demand to exclude wine from deposit refund systems. This demand is also supported by the European Parliament and should be introduced within the framework of the proposal by the year 2029.
Even though the Czech minister and the Belgian minister immediately expressed their reservations about the unequal treatment of brewers at the supreme meeting on December 18, they gave their consent. Belgium, which is now in the rotating presidency of the EU and should therefore remain neutral in negotiations between governments, hopes that an agreement with the parliament will be reached by the beginning of March.
Ignacio Sánchez Recarte, secretary general of the European wine industry association, the Comité Européen des Entreprises Vin, which represents over 7,000 winegrowers and vintners throughout Europe, does not share the brewers' reservations. He told Euronews that a market dominated by multinational brewery conglomerates cannot be compared with an industry that consists almost entirely of small national producers.
More than 99% of the domestic wine industry consists of very small to medium-sized businesses, said Sánchez Reacarte. He also questioned the validity of the legal arguments put forward by the breweries. In his opinion, his organization has strived to provide decision-makers with "relevant and adequate" information for their own industry.
"It is not my role to evaluate whether the beer industry should have this or that goal, because that depends on the specific characteristics of the industry itself," Sánchez Recarte declared. "Therefore, brewers should mind their own business and concentrate on their own obligations."
Brewers of Europe has shared a short legal analysis with Euronews that the association sent to the European Commission last year. In it, it argues that wine and beer are competing products "at least partially interchangeable with each other," and that rules favoring one industry over the other would distort the market.
Simon Spillane, the lobby's chief operating officer, said that brewers already occupy "a leading position" when it comes to sustainable packaging, citing the example of beer bottles that can be reused around 165 times before they are crushed and recycled after 30 years. They already support the reuse and recycling systems introduced in many countries.
"That's why we are advocating for an ambitious regulation concerning packaging and packaging waste. But we also need equal conditions in packaging legislation that allows beer and other alcoholic beverages to be treated according to the same rules. Every industry should contribute in the same way to achieve the goals and support the collection systems," said Spillane. "Any other approach means a competitive disadvantage for brewers."
The Biden administration releases economic criminals
Tim Whitehouse, former attorney for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and executive director of Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, praised the recent improvements by the Biden administration in enforcing environmental law, but also conceded that such efforts face much resistance. "It takes years of reliable funding and political support to develop a good program for enforcing the law," he told me. "Congressional instability not only demoralizes EPA staff, but also undermines their ability to think strategically long-term."
The EPA's problems are not identical, but comparable to those of the Ministry of Justice. Its Environment and Natural Resources Division (ENRD) deals with environmental crime. Uhlmann, the Deputy Assistant Administrator for Law Enforcement, was, before joining the EPA, from 1990 to 2007 head of the environmental crime section. The EPA sends its most serious civil and criminal cases to the ENRD, which, as a rather poorly funded authority, often relies on others to decide which battles to fight. In fiscal year 2022, the EPA transferred fewer cases (88) to the Department of Justice since 2000 and completed the fewest civil proceedings since that date. As mentioned in the project for environmental integrity, the EPA completed an average of 94 civil proceedings even under Trump and transferred 106 cases per year to the Ministry of Justice.
The general procedure of the Ministry of Justice in connection with economic crime cases has been examined in detail by the adherents. Observers have praised some steps introduced by the Ministry under Merrick Garland as Minister of Justice - for example, the creation of a database for environmental crime. However, Biden's Ministry of Justice has also relied heavily on the main witness programs that allow companies to delay or avoid criminal prosecution and encourage them to report individual collaborators to avoid more comprehensive charges. Kenneth Polite Jr., the former Deputy Assistant Attorney General in the Criminal Division, revised the division's enforcement guidelines for companies to limit prosecutions.
Debate about the shutdown fuels the Republicans' conflict
The opponents of the spending, the conservatives in the House of Representatives, have opposed the party leaders and have caused a series of votes to fail. Thus, they protested against the latest spending agreement of President Mike Johnson with the Democratic leaders, which, according to them, does not foresee sufficient budget cuts.
Even now it is possible for the Louisiana Republican to get out of the way on the issue, but the final date for the deliberation of four of the twelve annual budgets is January 19. Johnson has publicly stated that he will not support a transitional law called "Continuing Resolution" to extend the deadline for those four draft laws to the deadline of the remaining eight, February 2.
In view of the fact that there are only nine days left until that deadline, the leader of the Republican faction in the Senate, Mitch McConnell, announced that Congress must pass a "Continuing Resolution" to keep the government running. This means that the Speaker of the House could soon break a promise, with which he primarily wanted to appease the right wing of his party. Such a maneuver could cause a lively ideological debate about the role of Republicans in matters of spending reduction, and that could lead to a partial government shutdown or Johnson's removal from office.
Congressman Matt Rosendale of Montana declared to Newsweek: "I have clearly stated that 'Continuing Resolutions' are not the appropriate way to fund our government, since the Budget Act of 1974 provides for the approval of 12 appropriations bills. We have had more than enough time, and if the leaders do not instruct the committees to do their work and let the members of Congress vote, then that is the reason for the failure."
The Speaker of the House of Representatives, Mike Johnson, at the U.S. Capitol on December 12, 2023 in Washington, D.C. Johnson faces a rebellious Republican faction that is unable to reach an agreement on the level of budget expenditures. Photo: Kevin Dietsch/Getty Images
Rosendale, who is part of the far-right Freedom Caucus group, was one of those who caused Wednesday's vote to fail. According to him, the total sum of Johnson's proposal is too high and insufficient to reduce the state's 34 trillion dollar debt.
Rosendale was also one of the 71 Republicans who opposed the Fiscal Responsibility Act: the law on fiscal responsibility, negotiated between the Democrats and former Speaker Kevin McCarthy, which determines the basic conditions for Johnson's recent negotiations with the Democratic leader in the Senate, Charles Schumer.
While Johnson praised the merits of his agreement, which allows for savings of about 16 billion dollars, the Freedom Caucus is of the opinion that he could have achieved more. Moderate Republicans, who supported McCarthy's agreement, consider this stance unrealistic and contrary to the Republicans' goal of forcing Congress to approve the twelve bills individually and not to combine them with a so-called omnibus procedure in a single vote as in recent years.
"A new year, but the same idiotic behavior from some," Republican Congressman Mike Lawler of New York told Newsweek. "Since there will be no omnibus procedure, every bill must be deliberated and negotiated separately. It seems we will probably need more time for that. And I do not support a shutdown - so I also have no problem with a short-term 'Continuing Resolution' so that this process can be brought to a good end."
It would be the first time since 1996 that Congress approved all twelve draft laws separately. According to Lawler, it is worth approving the four draft laws with a delay, to ensure an orderly process. If Congress does not succeed in approving the twelve draft laws by December, a one percent budget reduction will be applied to defense and non-defense spending, according to the Fiscal Responsibility Act.
Congressman Thomas Massie of Kentucky - probably one of the Republican Party's most fervent opponents of spending - was not among those who protested the vote on Wednesday. He did, however, declare that a one-year "Continuing Resolution" with the consequence of a one percent reduction in spending is the most practical way to ensure the functioning of the government and at the same time end the squabbling with the risk.
The most responsible way to achieve cost reduction, according to Massie, is to approve all draft laws. Many Republicans, however, do not necessarily want to risk a shutdown and thus a percentage reduction in defense spending. The urgency with which the draft laws must be approved could contribute to a sufficient number of Republicans aligning with Democrats to extend the deadline for the first four draft laws and reach an agreement on funding government work, even if that would mean Johnson could face problems with some right-wing hardliners.
"It [the percentage reduction] should be a motivation and a means of pressure to approve the twelve draft laws separately," Massie declared to Newsweek. "In my opinion, we could first approve a 'Continuing Resolution', then exchange our arguments, and when we then face that small obstacle, hopefully everyone will be motivated to act reasonably. That's how I would do it."
The supervisory authority approves new ETFs on Bitcoin - a milestone for cryptocurrencies
The American stock exchange supervisory authority Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) gave the green light on Wednesday for exchange-traded funds (ETFs) in bitcoins. This is a long-awaited step by supporters of digital currencies and criticized by financial observers skeptical of the crypto industry.
The authority has approved ten ETFs that invest in bitcoins, including funds from industry giants such as Blackrock and Fidelity, but also from smaller financial companies.
"The fact that we have approved today the listing on the stock exchange and the trading of certain bitcoin products traded on the stock exchange does not mean that we welcome or approve bitcoins," SEC chief Gary Gensler declared in a statement. Investors should continue to be cautious given the numerous risks associated with bitcoins and products whose value is linked to cryptocurrencies."
He added that the approval of bitcoin funds does not mean that funds or exchange-traded products (ETPs) based on other digital currencies or assets will be approved by the SEC.
"What is important is the fact that today's approval is limited to ETPs that contain a specific non-currency-related product, namely Bitcoin. With this, we are in no way signaling a readiness to allow approval standards for crypto-assets. The approval also says nothing about the SEC's stance regarding the status of other crypto-assets under US securities laws or about the non-compliance of certain crypto-asset market participants with securities laws," Gensler said.
For years, the SEC has rejected applications from similar funds. Last year, the US Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled that the SEC's refusal to approve Grayscale's application to convert a derivatives fund was illegal. This fund was to be converted into a fund that would invest directly in Bitcoin. The court described the SEC's stance as "unmotivated and arbitrary."
Gensler has declared that he is - in view of these circumstances and those that have been presented in more detail in the approval decision - of the opinion that the most practicable way forward is to approve the listing and trading of these bitcoin-spot-ETP parts.
The eagerly awaited approval was welcomed as a milestone for digital currencies. According to its proponents, it increases access to bitcoin investments and could lead to wider acceptance of cryptocurrencies as a serious financial investment. The price of bitcoin has exploded in recent months from just over $25,000 in September to over $45,000. This is partly due to the fact that many bitcoin investors believe that ETFs will create greater demand for this asset.
The opponents of the decision strongly criticized the SEC on Wednesday evening.
Dennis M. Kelleher, co-founder, president and CEO of Better Markets, said that the approval is a "historic mistake". It not only unleashes crypto thieves on tens of millions of investors and pensioners, but probably also undermines the stability of financial markets.
Kelleher further stated that "the seemingly lawless crypto industry has reached its lowest point in view of the masses of arrests, convictions, insolvencies, lawsuits, scandals, massive losses and millions of victims among investors and customers. Who would have thought that the SEC would support it by approving a proven and reliable form of investment. Thus, the SEC makes it possible to mass market a worthless, volatile and deceptive financial product to American citizens."
30% more reports about the use of the Russian language in Ukraine - RT Russia and former Soviet Union
To defuse the area, the authorities appeal to the population to bring sand.
The number of reports submitted to the Ukrainian authorities about people speaking Russian increased by 30% last year. The authorities in Kyiv are actively encouraging the population to report such cases, apparently to "protect" the country from Russian influence.
According to the information from the office of the national language protection commissioner, 3,692 violations against the language law were reported in 2023. Kyiv, Kharkiv, and Odesa are "still at the top concerning the number of violations. This year, one of the priorities of the communal authorities should therefore be to strictly monitor that the language rights of citizens are respected in all sectors of public life," said Taras Kremen, the public mediator for languages in Ukraine.
Kremen also confirmed that a fine of 3,400 Hryvnia (89 dollars) had been imposed on a Kyiv taxi driver who had addressed his customers in Russian. The public mediator drew the public's attention to the fact that there is "a detailed algorithm of actions in case the right to receive information or services in the state language is violated". He appealed to the population to immediately report such cases on the mediator's website.
In 2019, Ukraine approved a law that mandates the use of the Ukrainian language in all sectors of public life, including government, medicine, science, education, and media. Violations are subject to fines. Since the beginning of the military conflict with Russia in 2022, Ukraine has been conducting a total de-Russification campaign, which, according to parliamentarians, is necessary to protect itself against Russian influence. Local authorities have completely banned works of art, performances, books, films, songs, and instruction in the Russian language in schools and universities, and have recommended that schoolchildren speak Ukrainian with each other even during breaks.
Last autumn, a young musician was briefly arrested and forced to apologize via video message after he had performed songs by the Soviet singer Viktor Tsoi on the streets of Lviv. The dismissal of several teachers who had spoken Russian with their students also caused a public outcry.
The secretary of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, Oleksiy Danilov, had previously declared that the Russian language must disappear from Ukrainian territory, because it is "an element of hostile propaganda and a brainwashing of the population".
According to Moscow's opinion, such laws violate the rights of the Russian population, which makes up about half of Ukraine's inhabitants. The spokeswoman for the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Maria Zakharova, declared in February that Kyiv's "discriminatory campaign" against the language was becoming increasingly "outrageous". In a survey conducted last September by the International Institute of Sociology in Kyiv, 45% of respondents indicated that linguistic discrimination was the most frequent type of prejudice in Ukraine.
Celeste is my favourite "small, good freeware game versus big commercial game blown up with not very detailed graphics" corruption arc, because getting the original double dash is a power-up without context in a treasure chest, and in the commercial game that makes me cry.
In general, I really like the interaction of the two games. The advantage of short stories is that you can "jump to the good part." This can be more captivating and satisfying. The advantage of long stories is that you can give the action elements a much greater emotional weight. Nothing happens immediately, but in return, you also get more.
The highlight of Celeste, the commercial game, is actually just the Pico-8 game, and that has been expanded with a mechanical and narrative construction of several hours, so that it becomes much, much harder. In Celeste, one is so proud of the small parent game that one continuously adds references like the monument, the progression of "2000 M ... 2500 M ...", the power-up, the flag at the top. One can play the original game directly from the start screen!
Celeste is neither "the good version" nor "the finished version" of Pico-8, it is just another version of the same main story. For someone who likes both short and long stories, it is truly interesting and great to see the connection that has been created so obviously.
It would have been possible to develop between the two versions yet another medium-length variant that tells the same story in an extended and expressive way, but with a shorter duration and with less crazy production values. I believe that would have been my preferred variant, especially as an arc of emotional tension. Instead, the main arc of tension in the commercial game for individual players is only a small part of it. Above all, it wants to be a great playground for the world's most popular platform physics, which in my opinion is still fine.
