I have only needed full anaesthesia once so far during a single operation. This was a "small" neurosurgical intervention to give my brain more space, because I was born with a disease that caused symptoms after I had children (Chiari malformation). The moment I woke up I have never forgotten and I relive it a little bit every time I watch medical shows, especially those with a neurosurgeon. 😂 Hospital Playlist has been on my list for a long time, and I'm really enjoying it right now. #kdrama
My surgeon really thinks of everything. He called me the day before because it was going to snow, and when the care team took care of me the moment I woke up from the anesthesia in the recovery room, my surgeon realized that I had opened my eyes and the bandage was on my eyes. I mean all that, plus still doing the operation. But I was still disoriented. That was one of the things that horrified me the most. I slept and it was already over.
I had my period, but I had to take it off. That's why they gave me that mesh underwear that you wear after giving birth. But in the operating room, you are completely undressed and covered with a sheet. Sometime before I became alert, a kind nurse changed my underwear. Unlike during births, where I was alert and received help, or from a baby, no one has ever done anything so private for me. That was also my only time in the intensive care unit. I had to go to the intensive care unit as a precaution, because of the type of operation.
I had to rest a lot because of my operation, so I watched seasons 1-3 of Grey's Anatomy. It helped me that McDreamy was a neurosurgeon. I paid attention to how the patient was positioned, to be able to imagine what was happening to me. Since my operation in 2018, Hospital Playlist has shown more about neurosurgery than any other medical show I've seen since Grey's. How wonderful that there is art and entertainment to give meaning to our lives.
Thanks to Hospital Playlist, I could transplant a liver.
Wow!
I often thought about how millennials were the last generation that was able to establish relationships with artists, without being expected to also view them in a critical way.
We grew up in an era of media flourishing with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We knew how to be fascinated by things without having to ponder where they came from, because at that time it was not so easy to find that out.
We did not have to question the pedestal on which we placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong need for nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the show together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes appear at the same time and everyone watches when they feel like it and puts "spoiler warnings" at the beginning of their social media posts or discusses it in closed groups.
Subconsciously we wanted to belong to that universal community that could do all that.
Why do so many of us still obsessively watch series like "The Office" or films like "Anchorman" with so many references in one line that would be memes today?
We have repeated all those sayings, assuming that most of them already understand them.
Today one cannot assume that everyone understands something, even if it spreads virally.
There is far too much and there is no possibility to systematize it. Who knows if we will ever get out of this abundance?
We are caught in a vicious circle that forces us to constantly discover new content, only to realize that the artist is broke or a bigot.
Therefore we are forced to hold on to our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that please us could also have made big mistakes.
We establish parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on one or the other's toes along the way.
Since we have lost our collective consciousness in connection with the media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked later when the person falls.
We are in a phase of profound change and I am curious where we will finally settle.
