It's an absolute niche problem, but if you want to build/customize robot figures, it's really getting on your nerves that you HAVE to build something that's made for war and killing.
Like the noughties. Then there were Bionicles. These were actually adventurers/heroes with very elemental powers and with different personalities and hobbies and so on, but before and after there was only something like Warhammer, Gundam, Battletech, where everything is designed to be a weapon and is staged in the accompanying media in a completely unnecessary way.
It's clear, those other sources KNOW that "war is bad", but then they continue to sell killing machines as figures and merchandise. So what do we want to do?
In my opinion, the solution is to separate between their appearance and that fictitious intent, as one also does in the real world with tanks and jets, but my brain has PROBLEMS with that.
Because the figures look cool, and I like how they are built and how their design reflects certain characteristic traits, but then with every set it says: "By the way, here is your laser sword and your (at least one) pistol!"
This probably has largely to do with the fact that toys for boys almost always have something to do with violence, such as GI Joe and Transformers, but let's be honest, we are in the current year.
I'm already looking forward to seeing Berry's pacifist robot family squashed in 3D ;)
@user25 Oooh, that's the idea, in any case, as soon as I have the skills to do that.
A self-proclaimed anarchist who wants to keep his identity secret gives his DNA to a biotechnology company to get a dubious overview of his "ancestry". What could possibly go wrong?
My wife wanted that as a starting point. Without going too deeply into it here, she believes that some of her ancestors are actually not her ancestors. I would like to support her and see the effect of a genetic drift based on a small control experiment. We know quite a lot about our family.
Perhaps there really is one or the other in my family who was unfaithful, but if one considers my family roots, for the most part poor, all affairs probably happened in mostly homogeneous villages, in small marked and ethnic ghettos, lol.
My grandmother left her husband for his brother, and I have a great-uncle on the other side of the family who left his wife for her aunt. My family might be going for a walk, but it won't get very far.
And now my wife is in a bad mood, because my "extraction" went much faster than expected. I'm in pain, maybe her genome shouldn't be so easily supplicated.
The results are here and - surprisingly please - they correspond perfectly to my family history. 89.9% British and Irish, most concentrated in the Scottish Borders region, in eastern Ireland, Wales and Cornwall. However, there isn't much Breton, perhaps because it's either so close to Cornwall that it can't be distinguished for me, or my Breton family doesn't originate from there.
Being around 40, I was a bit worried that there might be children, about whom I knew nothing. Until now, only one of my cousins has abandoned his children (perhaps).
Fuck you, King Louis XIV, one of your descendants is an anarchist!
Complicated woman: So, with the DNA test, are you now going to refer to your Scottish and Irish parts?
I, in a kilt with Johnston's squares and reading "Elders of Ireland": No, that wouldn't work with my life.
