Times to relax are rare as an academic, but in those moments when you're not sitting at the desk, you have the best ideas. 💭
Trying harder to publish more does not always lead to better results. One must not forget to relax if one wants to become a better scientist.
This is how I recharge my batteries again:
Clean both halves of the brain. 🧠
As scientists, we generally use the analytical part of our brain. But if I use the creative part (e.g. to play guitar, paint, etc.) and also the analytical part of my brain, I have the impression of having increased my mental capacities. This way I improve in both areas.
Train the muscles, not just the head. 💪
Sport is not just something for future triathletes or people who want to look better. Sport also improves the quality of life. Thoughts, mood, productivity: everything is connected. Taking a break and stepping away from the desk makes the time at the desk much more productive.
Permission to relax. 📺
Recharging the batteries doesn't necessarily mean that one has to acquire new habits. A good film or a good book can have the same effect as creative work and physical activity. The important thing is to become aware that it is okay to relax and do nothing. There is no room for feelings of guilt!
I've felt that these things help me to relax. But there are still many others. What doesn't one do to stay enthusiastic about science and not get a burnout?🤔
#academic #science #promotion #phdlife #typical
Also, my life is just very difficult.
