Perhaps a fisheye lens is a bit exaggerated for a birdhouse.
One always learns again.
I should have known better, since I had already built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more at the weekend, as soon as I have installed the second one.
Let me just say that the birds will have a better internet connection than me in 2015.
That is at least the plan.
The box that already contains a spark sends a lot of WLAN data.
The other one will need a bit more work to go online.
Ok, I hung up the new birdhouse today. This is what it looks like in its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. Someone asks: "What exactly is there?"
At the top is one of those ESP32 camera boards with a camera with a fisheye lens and an IR-LED that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the curious shape of the plastic box is the rotatable side of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to build everything around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, everything is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I photographed neither the cell nor the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In that grey box hanging on the side of the snowplow, the battery is located.
When it is charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
This is once a feature as it should be. That also gives the birds a bit of private space.
At the beginning, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for that installation. The old access points that I replaced last autumn would not have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover that part very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had the intention of installing a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and pointing it down towards the garden.
Perhaps I'll still do that when I install additional nesting boxes with cameras. I'll probably use that for the parts that are further away from the house.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It went offline just an hour after the sun went down.
Perhaps the battery didn't charge further three hours before the sun went down, because there wasn't enough light.
Not even half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I probably have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have any telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
In general, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And perhaps a battery that is at least theoretically capable of operating all night.
Oh, yes, and another goal.
Fisheye is an old surface.
But I am already looking for parts at Digikey, so that I can build my own board exactly for this case.
Not yet. We'll see.
And it is still offline.
Super.
According to the solar cells on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of direct sunlight.
Let's wait another one or two hours to see what happens - or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is simple.
It turned out that 5V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen of the USB-C breakout board I used to connect to the charger.
I have swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and she is still offline.
It looks like I have to do a new start that activates Tasmota's reset function.
I think the panel is worthless. I have now ordered a larger one and hope that it works.
Look what I found in my workshop.
In a 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partly covered by a plant) that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I turn it on.
I believe I have to wait until tomorrow to know if it's enough to install or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the 2021 panel and it should provide 12V for max. 1.2 A.
Either something is not in order with the panel or with my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
They changed the data and the ones I have are wrong.
The old as well as the new title of the list indicates that it is a 12V 10W.
That's why I never delete old emails.
Oh, look! He went online again about an hour ago for about half a minute.
Perhaps the panel charged the battery just long enough for a 38-second operating time. For that, it only needed a little more than two hours.
I thought once: Today it is cloudy. I am therefore not sure if the solar panel (probably broken) is able to produce enough electricity at all.
Let's wait and see.
Update: I have installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
He could still settle down as soon as the sun sets, but let's give him a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to see if it is online or not.
The connection time is on average 102 ms. Not great, but not miserable either.
