The development of humanity progresses continuously. Even in difficult times, we continue to develop and adapt. In the markets, prosperity is still great and technological progress is advancing. With the recent discovery of Ignniat, humanity has catapulted itself to unprecedented heights; but the greatest is yet to come. This new knowledge that has been bestowed upon humanity can only be described as divine intervention, and the gods will rejoice at our presence in heaven. The company Karascene has had Ignniat thoroughly examined and assesses the potential of this mineral as very great. And no fear: according to the examinations, there are no side effects or problems with decomposing Ignniat. This mineral is destined for greater purposes.
January 14, 2543, 10:26 PM.
In a click. The same stream repeated itself again and again: the day the world had been devastated. My father would switch the channel every time he saw that I couldn't look away. My stomach tightened seeing his worried face. I always feel bad when that stream comes on, because it awakens so many memories in me, but not very good ones. With a sigh, I stand up to get other thoughts. I always tried to make him smile and chase away his bad mood by doing him a small favor, but today I am tired.
I carefully approached the door and called to my father: "I'm going down for a bit, dinner is in the fridge." No answer. What else. Most likely he heard me, he'll probably come down by himself. I closed the door softly and sighed once more, when it completely closed. I had almost forgotten to put my hand on the cold metal scanner to lock the door. If there was anything particular about this apartment, it was its modern technology, but most buildings had such. For a long time now, no other technology had been used here.
On that cold and rainy night, I took my long-planned exploratory walk through Paltricus - a privilege reserved for those who had escaped the mutation by fleeing or by having incredible luck. The night was illuminated by shining stars that were already thousands of years old. It must be lonely in the universe. Paltricus was a beautiful city, but one felt more like in a box here and not like in a luxurious place to live. The city was packed with apartments, houses, and other buildings; most of them had several hundred stories, thanks to Ignniat. This mineral had proven to be a true fortune for technology and architecture and had expanded our living bases. However, the public knows very little about this mineral, especially because it is kept strictly secret.
To free myself from my dark thoughts, I set off to drink a coffee in my favorite place. Most people avoid it, because there's a rumor that an infected person was there. That's what they call those who have been infected with the virus. That has never worried me - I've had a lot of luck in my life - and the owner is a great guy. Who would give up a free coffee to be able to have a pleasant conversation late at night?
When I entered, my discomfort was chased away by a sweet warmth and the smell of fresh coffee spread in my nose. Anton, the owner of the place, stood as always behind the counter. The place was practically empty, with the exception of a couple of people in the back. After the long walk, I approached the bar exhausted, let myself fall onto one of the stools and sighed. I see Anton and he brings me the usual. "Hello Lilith, a long night?", his hoarse voice echoed through the twists of my brain. "Something like that," I replied tiredly and became more and more tired from second to second.
To chase away my tiredness I took a couple of sips of coffee in front of me. "Is business still bad since that story with the infected...?" I spoke quietly so as not to scare away the last guests in Anton's place. He nodded while wiping a little with a cloth. This place is actually a bar, but I had never come here to drink a drink. Behind me one heard a murmur, but the conversation between Anton and Anton and me remained rather short that evening. With a short sign of farewell and a little more energy than before I left the place.
It was usually not the best idea to walk late at night on dark streets. But that was still better than staying in that stuffy apartment and listening to the neighbors having sex. You heard them more often than your own music. With a short sigh, I looked back at the street in front of me. I'm probably going to Al's pawn shop to pass the time by looking if there's any interesting old stuff there. When I heard footsteps right behind me, I regretted my decision. Maybe I'm worrying too much, but in this neighborhood, you only found yourself there if you wanted to be robbed or beaten up. The neighborhood was known for its mafia and gang crime...
Isn't that funny? Only half of humanity is still here and yet we can't stop hurting each other. I went faster, the pawn shop was just around the corner, and inside I was safe. When I stood in front of an illuminated sign with the inscription "Alborn's pawn shop", a quick glance over my shoulder confirmed that I was no longer being pursued. With a slower step, I entered the shop. It was a bit out of the way, as Alborn often took in mutants who lived without permission in Paltricus. It was dark in the shop and AI was strangely not there either. No fugitives. Nothing. Something was not right here.
I slipped into the back of the shop, where I heard a murmur and hushed voices behind a metal grate that could be removed with a few turns. I crawled into the ventilation shaft - at the moment the simplest and safest method. As I squeezed through it, I heard conversations between strangely dressed men. Then I saw Al, chained up. It was clear that they would catch him one day.
I really liked Alborn, but this here was too big a number for me. I don't always have to stick my nose into other people's business, especially not if they're just having a dispute with every authority in town. Still, I couldn't do otherwise. With a deep sigh, I slowly lifted the garter from under me out of its fastening and crept down into the silent room. "Psst. Al. Al!" I whispered, and when he didn't answer, I raised my voice. "Lilith? What are you doing here? You have to go, otherwise they can get to you."
"What you're saying...", I said softly to myself. While we tried to untangle the chains around his arms, we heard voices approaching and the silent footsteps grew louder. "Quick! Get back into the vent and disappear. Don't come back under any circumstances. If we were to see each other, then not in this city." He spoke quickly and the panic in his eyes didn't exactly help to calm me down. I followed his advice. I couldn't stay here any longer. Damn it, Al. After leaving the ventilation shaft, I ran away. It hurt to lose such a loyal friend. Did they want to take him to the other... city? So many things went through my head. I was so angry, but also sad. I had dealt intensively with the outer cities and with the capital of the infected. It was called Alcatraz, just like the prison. The name fit quite well with what I had read. Not to mention that the non-mutants had cut off all connections with the infected lands. A tragedy.
A deafening silence accompanied me on the way home. The thoughts in my head rushed and almost tore me apart, because I hadn't been able to help Al. When I finally arrived home after that terrible walk, I was on the verge of tears, and the sounds of the thunder coming from the clouds above me could instill fear and anxiety in anyone. My father had already fallen asleep on the sofa. A rerun of a film from 10-12 years ago was just playing. With a sigh, I quietly slipped into my room. I let myself fall onto the bed. I could barely keep my eyes open and almost immediately fell asleep.
EXPLOSION
January 19, 2543, 2:34 PM.
The time had flown by. A few days ago, Alborn had been taken away. I didn't know where. But they had gone somewhere with him. The men's clothing had become familiar to me, but I simply couldn't remember where from. With a sigh, I placed my hands on the system in front of me that glowed red and violet - hacking it would have been child's play for me. I doubt they secured it additionally... Perhaps it would be better to leave it alone anyway. But of course, I pushed my moral reservations aside. My finger moved as if by itself across the keyboard and called up different monitors. Damn, I'm good. I was quite well-known on some websites, they called me "SPÉRT" there. A name that is quite easy to remember. But I admit that I use the name SP3RT on every website, but I like the thought that I got it from others.
I downloaded the surveillance camera footage to my mobile device and examined each one intensely. Nothing. As if they had never been there. That makes no sense. The cameras are well secured, even against remote access. How...? DAMN IT. Full of disgust, I stood up to chase the thoughts out of my head. I went to the door and grabbed my keys. "I'll be right back, Dad." Silence. That's normal, he never answered anyway. He was probably busy with something more important than me again.
When I left the apartment, I felt a shiver down my spine. A strange feeling. I ignored it and forced myself to go to Al's shop to do some investigations. My legs, however, carried me to Anton's small bar. It was quite quiet there and I urgently needed someone to talk to. Who would have been more suitable than a bartender who owes me?
It was also unusually full, crowded with people I had never seen before. Anton usually worked alone and was certainly quite stressed because of the crowds of people. "I'd like a coffee." I deliberately spoke in a low tone to annoy him a little. He sighed briefly and I had to laugh softly when I saw the relief on his face. "Devil, Lilith, don't scare me like that...", he said softly, with a tired voice. "It looks like you have a lot to do... Should I help you? There's a lot going on here." Even though I had no desire to serve those annoying people, I felt sorry for Anton, because he had to deal with that crowd alone. "Would you do that? You'll get your money later...", he murmured and looked at me with his dog eyes. Advanced war tactics...
After I had exchanged my clothes for a work uniform, I helped Anton at the bar. Despite his constant attempts to flirt and attract my attention, which to be honest didn't bother me at all, the work went smoothly. I will talk to Anton after the shift is over. I have to scribble Al out of my head, even though I know I will do further investigations in his pawn shop after this shift at the bar, but still...
Flames erupted from Thassalin's throat when the colossal Thraki set fire to a specific piece of forest and then turned around to detect movements. Curiously, the disturbing growl behind him ceased when he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What's that supposed to mean, Tenuk, you've already changed into a Thracian once!"
"When I fly myself, that's completely different from being suddenly grabbed and pulled into the air by a pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not of the same opinion as Nyssi. He looked less nervous than usual and his claws were dug so deeply into Thassalin's back that the Thraki was bleeding. However, that didn't seem to bother Thassalin. Nevertheless, he realized that he had scared his new friends, and sat down in a corner.
"I'm sick, but I've lost something. I had to take care of that!"
"But did you also have to drag us along with you?" Tenuk murmured, when he slid down from Thassalin's back and slithered down his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! Our great and strong warrior we left in the shit! How is he supposed to follow us now?"
"He'll surely let something get into his head...", Nyssi murmured. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not stupid."
"That's good, but can Retvik go by car?"
Nyssi grumbled and turned towards Tenuk. "Of course he can go by car."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've also never seen him drive a car as small as Kayel's. And he only started driving to work because you always drive. He only has his bike."
They are interrupted by a burst of laughter. Thassalin suddenly seemed to be having enormous fun with something, but no one knew why he was laughing. It lasted a little too long until Thassalin quieted down.
"I'm sick, but I put your gigantic friend in armor on a child's mini-bike from Temthan. That was laugh-out-loud funny! I wish I had some kind of telepathy. A beautiful imagination! One that I can't share!"
Kayel laughed, because he could imagine what was going through Thassalin's head. "Yes, you are right. But what have you lost and why did you fly away so suddenly?"
Thassalin growled, stood up and disappeared. When he returned after a short time, he threw something dead at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare dragon-like creature, golden-white in color. Only its head was missing. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR ITS CRIES. I FREEZE ITS BLOOD. SOMETHING FORCES ME TO PROTECT AND TO HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE."
The gigantic Thraki suddenly became completely quiet. Nyssi and Kayel were also surprised and directed their gaze at a gap in the glacier. Something big and black stared at them, snorting. Whatever it was, the creature spread two pairs of gigantic wings and flew towards Thassalin without paying attention to the three smaller beings among them. Kayel and Tenuk just managed to get to safety, but Nyssi was caught and almost crushed on Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to that attack by grabbing Nyssi and throwing him with her skillful and incredibly long tail onto his back, before rising into the air. The black creature with double wings followed them with great speed.
Kayel clicked his tongue in disgust, while he took his rifle from his back and opened a pouch that contained an ammunition belt. He hung the belt around his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thrak and the monster were no longer visible.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you turn into something that can fly?" Kayel asked.
"Do you want to follow them?"
"Yes, clear!"
"But... one of them is a gigantic monster!"
"Yes, and then? I'm standing here with a rifle in my hand and could shoot immediately. But it would be good to see him to be able to hit him."
Tenuk flinched, then he took a step back to have more space. With a slight painful growl, Tenuk's body stretched, his skin changed into scales and his arms into wings. He transformed into a normal, light blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"It's raining."
As a trained Thracian, Tenuk now had real scales along his back. And from his back had grown two spines, which was practical, so Kayel could hold onto them. It took a little too long for Tenuk to take off, but once he was in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to pursue the others.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized that they were not alone. A second dark creature had settled below them in the air and Tenuk had only just managed to avoid a collision.
"So this is that gigantic, terrifying monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel rubbed his forehead. He tried to shoot the second beast, but missed and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too busy concentrating on the flight after Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other beast was chasing them. Kayel had turned awkwardly to keep an eye on the monster. The fact that it was chasing them was an advantage for Kayel, as he could better aim at it and shoot. Two arrows hit the beast's upper wings. It screamed in pain and descended below the trees. Kayel was not sure if it was still chasing them, but it certainly couldn't keep up with them.
Nyssi stood desperately and with all her might in front of them, while Thassalin spewed and spat flames at the sooty monster. The creature was definitely injured. It seemed to be somewhat enraged, but not ready to give up. The fireballs did not seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin stretched out, Nyssi took the opportunity to grab her own weapon, a good, old rifle. Even if it wasn't made for such purposes, could the pellets at least scare away the black beast?
No, as it didn't seem. The creature just snorted and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Luckily, Thassalin was agile enough, despite his size, and dodged, but Nyssi let out a scream when she almost lost her balance on Thassalin's too-smooth scales by a fingernail.
"HOW DO WE KILL HER?", Nyssi shouted.
"SIT ON YOUR HEAD!"
"THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin roared and then drew a circle closer to the peak that he called his home. The dark beast followed, but panicked a little when a ray of fire touched it from behind. It hadn't realized that it was no longer alone. It panicked even more when Thassalin slowed down and slammed his tail against its head, pushing it off the path.
Murmuring and bubbling, she flew up and spat into the air. Suddenly everything went dark, as if the monster had sucked up the light of the sky, replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
When Thassalin suddenly saw nothing more, he tried to retreat. He felt himself scrape against the crowns of the trees, before he finally fell into a thicket. The beast seemed to know exactly where Thassalin had fallen and descended directly towards him, stretching out its black beak.
"Kayel!", Tenuk called out, as he slipped out of the fog and began to make circles, to find Nyssi and Thassalin in the dark. "What are we going to do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Nyssi barely managed to stand up. She was sure she had broken something, but her curious supernatural healing powers were already beginning to spread their effect. Unfortunately, this was not true for Thassalin. He rested, completely exhausted, against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get closer to Thassalin, but she could barely see more than two meters in front of her. Everything was dark and shrouded in terrifying shadows. And in those shadows, something was growling and snarling.
A horrible armored tail crashed to the ground near Nyssi and thrashed around her. However, she felt that the tail was only thrashing like a wild animal in all directions, without trying to touch her. The beast, what little Nyssi saw or heard of it, growled and tried to reach with its claws the shadows it had created. Something darted through the darkness, hit the monster and startled it.
Suddenly a shot from a rifle broke through the mist and the monster became silent, fell to the ground and remained there, motionless. The darkness around them disappeared and they saw what had happened: on the beast stood Kayel, all out of breath, holding his rifle in his hand.
"That was... the most spectacular shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel snapped into the air. His eyes were burning black and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, the color returned to his armor and his eyes regained their usual yellow color.
It took a moment until Nyssi understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed those particular shadow powers. He rarely used them, because they disturbed and frightened most people. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could use those powers even in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he also seemed to be quite surprised.
"Is everything alright with you?", Nyssi asked then.
"Yes, everything is okay with me. I killed something, everything will be good with me again soon." Kayel contemplated his work, while Tenuk flew down, sat next to him and transformed back into his usual Spast form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its fur was black as coal and shiny, but the slime stuck to its body. The creature had four wings and four limbs that all ended in long, sharp claws, and out of its skull grew two straight horns.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the devil they had in front of them, they heard a scream and something jumped out of a nearby bush. However, that creature did not reach them, because a familiar vehicle jumped into it from the side, so that the monster slid along and stopped at Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to risk anything. She grabbed her rifle, shot without thinking at its head, and the creature was instantly dead.
"Oops...", Retvik murmured from the driver's seat, before he awkwardly turned off the engine and got out of the truck. "Um, I didn't actually mean to do that. Is everything alright with you?"
"You missed the whole action," Tenuk grumbled. "Where were you?"
"You simply left me halfway. I came as fast as possible...", Retvik sighed. "May I ask what horrible beasts these are?"
Luckily, Thassalin, who had gotten back on his feet, was able to answer Retvik's question. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not too badly injured.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT HAVE LEFT HERE, WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible creature of God that we... helped to kill?" Tenuk stammered.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. MAYBE THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT HIM IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, ISN'T IT?" Thassalin limped towards Kayel and spat on his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT YOU ARE NOT AS BLOODTHIRSTY AND NOT AS CAPABLE OF KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES."
"Um... thanks... I think..." Kayel drew the curtains. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the beasts that were now definitely dead. Then she took out her favorite weapon, the stiletto adorned with the god of the dead, and began to saw off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards she went to the second one. Just as Nyssi was finished, the beasts suddenly went up in flames and turned into a pile of ashes within seconds. The same thing happened with the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
"Well, that's practical and impractical at the same time...", Nyssi sighed. "But at least I have the photos, I hope."
